document.title: Head Start Early Learning Outcomes Framework

E33A595287684280BECEAD6BD760DC59.description: Communicates to adults when hungry, thirsty, or has had enough to eat.

36BE3B34F98C4CDEAC8E28763C9CDC21.description: Sometimes makes nutritious choices with support from an adult.

6EDF20A522A6443EB8C82CBA9B78A68F.description: Expresses preferences about foods, specifically likes or dislikes, sometimes based on whether the food is nutritious.

D47FDA3D76D84BAB8E32B56BB0B5FCCC.description: Shows willingness to try new nutritious foods when offered on multiple occasions. Sometimes makes nutritious choices about which foods to eat when offered several choices, with support from an adult.

3D65CD58998E4FAEA7CB14D460B5BE0F.description: Child demonstrates increasing interest in engaging in healthy eating habits and making nutritious food choices.

10C50A01D2D548648CC8F4A5DB6639AD.description: Shows some understanding of safe and unsafe behaviors, such as not touching a hot stove.

CF61DB69AE984581B02736FA049703E1.description: Cooperates with adults when in unsafe situations, such as taking an adult’s hand to cross a street or being cautious around an unfamiliar dog.

05812C107D314DD5BC076F5158340333.description: Accepts adult guidance, support, and protection when encountering unsafe situations. Learns some differences between safe and unsafe play behaviors, such as not to stand on chairs or tables, or not to put small objects in mouth.

8808299AB38F45C3A9D27868A1E4FD79.description: Child uses safe behaviors with support from adults.

913326B308994AC5AAD0C1AD083C03CB.description: Puts on or takes off some articles of clothing, such as shoes, socks, coat, or hat.

6BDEA07470D54D689A1FDB97DED908A7.description: Shows increasing independence in self-care routines with guidance from adults.

E08EFAC3CE5B46F38514559D4C599A33.description: Participates in healthy care routines with more independence, such as washing hands, blowing nose, brushing teeth, or drinking from a cup.

D926C2BDE4F2464D828BDDC56B726DD0.description: Child demonstrates healthy behaviors with increasing independence as part of everyday routines.

5571C265C6114799A960E48EF92B9FB3.description: Uses hand tools in a variety of ways, such as a rolling pin with clay or play dough, or a toy shovel with sand.

A4BCE21187A4463193B9B3542B3420DF.description: Uses pincer grasp with thumb and fingers to manipulate small objects or handle tools, such as stringing small beads.

A839182A07104EE18BD63C43611D095E.description: Adjusts grasp with ease to new tools and materials.

17746DDBCEC846BB8E79749AF751B7C9.description: Adjusts grasp to use different tools for different purposes, such as a spoon, paintbrush, or marker.

6ECF0360E0464668819C8BD595585C1D.description: Child adjusts reach and grasp to use tools.

226805A6DE1D4387BB32358C32723302.description: Coordinates use of both hands to put things together, such as connecting blocks or linking toys.

5896621F64E84B4D9B0B0E7BC8813E6F.description: Uses hands efficiently for a variety of actions or activities, such as building with blocks, wiping up a spill, or feeding self.

06576E4DAB984D539FD9AA2C872AE958.description: Plans ways to use hands for various activities, such as stacking, building, connecting, drawing, painting, and doing self-care skills or routines.

60403AC2E70C45D39A86B5618F60CE81.description: Child uses hands for exploration, play, and daily routines.

9BF88E2F1071424A8C3484D4ECD01E42.description: Uses hand-eye coordination in handling books, such as turning pages, pointing to a picture, or looking for favorite page.

F74BBD32FEBF4FF8BF1DE3FEF9D49D84.description: Uses hand-eye coordination to manipulate objects and materials such as completing puzzles or threading beads with large holes.

AB476025D07541729EF10553F2E42C22.description: Uses hand-eye coordination when participating in routines, play and activities, such as putting on a mitten, painting at an easel, putting pieces of a puzzle together, or folding paper.

FB65AC2F723F44BDB77EC972C8A2411A.description: Child coordinates hand and eye movements to perform actions.

B6185A3547524C49ABEF8EF4195700A1.description: Adjusts position of body to fit through or into small spaces.

964EB44E5CD04E8C8E2A43CDF7A4BC3B.description: Maintains balance and posture while seated and concentrating, such as working with clay, blocks, or markers or looking at a book.

BA08AB53390B458CBB7D5D500CA69F74.description: Shows understanding of what size openings are needed for their body to move through. Learns about body size, such as doll clothes won’t fit on a child’s body or a child’s body won’t fit on dollhouse furniture.

1AF81BD6266849F686AC347AA81F2C8B.description: Child uses sensory information and body awareness to understand how their body relates to the environment.

63D26B02F53E4BD198EF14BDD9C888B1.description: Experiments with different ways of moving the body, such as dancing around the room.

5F8E4FD0A3AE4B628647F255021C87C5.description: Explores environments using motor skills, such as throwing, kicking, jumping, climbing, carrying, and running.

A1806CB8B7C84A0B875FFD04773975CB.description: Uses a variety of increasingly complex movements, body positions, and postures to participate in active and quiet, indoor and outdoor play.

EB72B118AD174D2E9C1C9D796AB242B0.description: Child demonstrates effective and efficient use of large muscles to explore the environment.

D4AA422D0528409D8BFA778BB3AEEF5B.description: Walks and runs, adjusting speed or direction depending on the situation.

7096C2DD4F404DCA97EA1896356C37E6.description: Coordinates movements and actions for a purpose.

1C4C130145AB4D01A0BC47AF23F4928D.description: Gains control of a variety of postures and movements including stooping, going from sitting to standing, running, and jumping.

FF05D9422B7540F084E9842C631FC4D9.description: Child demonstrates effective and efficient use of large muscles for movement and position.

B31FCAEFA615452A8F37C9256D8F01A8.description: Handles or explores objects or materials in different ways depending on perceptual information about the objects or materials, such as fragile, messy, or sticky properties.

74548A6C7BB34DC48A35D5586CA9FA43.description: Adjusts walking or running to the type of surface, such as a rocky, sandy, or slippery surface.

BD9B419094E5402D86B57EB93148467F.description: Coordinates perceptual information and motor actions to participate in play and daily routines, such as singing songs with hand motions or practicing self-care skills.

B4E0073179D34714A36CDFF1CBA80AB8.description: Child uses perceptual information in directing own actions, experiences, and interactions.

D932AA9871CD4B5CB7D5DC4F82A7A7CD.description: Modifies responses in social situations based on perceptual information, especially when meeting new people, such as hiding their face from an unfamiliar person.

B1BC891080DE43EF86DC9217C873C918.description: Adjusts ways of interacting with materials based on sensory and perceptual information, such as pressing harder on clay than on play dough to make something.

19AE8D73F05D492984929BFE5089D78E.description: Combines information gained through the senses to understand objects, experiences, and interactions.

16626A47522E4960AB1E3FFA171B8315.description: Observes others making things happen to understand the cause and effect relationship of intention and action, such as seeing an adult prepare to go outside and then going to get their own jacket.

DB5D8DD164ED4FB0BAF9F108622B4700.description: Child uses perceptual information to understand objects, experiences, and interactions.

A75C5E7823344A1DBAAB6A6B9AAE6DD4.description: Domain: Perceptual, Motor, and Physical Development

1F024B279949419396B010DF013294F5.description: Uses pretend play to try out solutions to everyday problems, such as ways to respond to stressful situations.

B73C702A8B974E5D8510D06E1564E4A0.description: Looks for props to use when telling or making up a story.

28CF6A35D6D74370ACAD91BA57114EC0.description: Seeks to involve others in pretend or make-believe play.

3BC3A7509B884C5093CE56113E52AEB3.description: Acts out routines, stories, or social roles using toys and other materials as props, such as setting toy dishes and cups on a table or pretending to shop for groceries.

3261B165E461494CBDDA7462F868577E.description: Child uses pretend play to increase understanding of culture, environment, and experiences.

2A662E7179E54F6ABD2F9307F48C2B28.description: Understands that some symbols have meaning, such as a sign or a drawing.

280A0429A0D44DF49B8C4468894D209E.description: Improvises with props during pretend play, such as using a towel for a blanket or making a cookie out of play dough.

B83D91BF69DF4D30AAA6260B2B40BCC3.description: Uses familiar objects to represent something else.

0C996DD9C8914193A548F076FDB806B6.description: Uses objects as symbols to represent other objects during pretend play, such as using blocks for toy cars or trucks.

2384A12697104FE28684C9225CBDE905.description: Child uses objects or symbols to represent something else.

4D71D98DB2FF40B994B34B4779E5FC0B.description: Imitates someone else’s conversation, such as in pretend play or on a toy phone.

E279B0B6002C496A9D7C8F64F4AE99D8.description: Watches and imitates adult actions involving multiple steps, such as getting spoons and forks to set a table.

4C16DD5FB310403BB6573F5577B3B67A.description: Imitates more complex actions, words, or signs at a later time in order to communicate, make, or do something.

AAB5EA70260E40818878A27BD128E739.description: Child observes and imitates sounds, words, gestures, actions, and behaviors.

4097E6C8BA4E4BEFAAF1518320EDF902.description: SUB-DOMAIN: IMITATION AND SYMBOLIC REPRESENTATION AND PLAY

F5879660D7D14412B9BBC9E978F5368D.description: Identifies characteristics of people, such as “Mom has black hair like me.”

437E6828B1B0450F84BF84B401224733.description: Sorts toys or other objects by color, shape or size.

B593384F4BA948C99A2B68628C1EC09A.description: Sorts objects into two groups based on a single characteristic, such as grouping toy animals separately from toy cars, or putting red socks and white socks in different piles.

E71E43F72D194FCDA9ACD3A7517AE0BC.description: Child uses matching and sorting of objects or people to understand similar and different characteristics.

3C50000FE72143CB8D7635D40AA583BE.description: Understands some effects of size or weight when picking up or moving objects.

9D3C085AE01B4D2684549BA5002C3BE6.description: Does puzzles with interlocking pieces, different colors and shapes.

C71AB72F2FBB46BB937DA664BBF9C8C0.description: Predicts or anticipates how things move through space, or fit together or inside other things, such as putting smaller objects into a small box and larger objects into a large box.

505E6DAA7D89461A8F022D2292A3BAAC.description: Child uses spatial awareness to understand objects and their movement in space.

1D96B165205D4103A512CD4CAF9ADB12.description: Uses fingers to show how old they are.

0DCC50E6F42F4EA4816A5E371ADA6712.description: Identifies “more” or “less” with a small number of items without needing to count them.

C2FE0C89F9F74838BE5948882480F37F.description: Counts small number of objects (2–3), sometimes counting the same object twice or using numbers out of order.

8946EAD8170E43D9AA36E76484AC02AC.description: Uses language to refer to quantity, such as using some number words or signs to identify small amounts, or using other words referring to quantity, such as a little, too much or a lot.

1070BA52C8DD43B2BED681984BADB421.description: Child develops sense of number and quantity.

1052D7A9B65F4BB7A32AD0CF25FEA60C.description: Plans ways to solve problems based on knowledge and experience, such as getting a stool to reach a book that is on a shelf after trying to reach it on tiptoes.

087725CD17A64758A3D48E198FA60B3E.description: Tries to fix things that are broken, such as putting a toy back together or using tape to repair a torn paper.

410BB3D5094B4EED912B6636149B118D.description: Uses problem-solving and experimenting to figure out solutions to everyday problems, including in social situations, such as when two children who both want to fit into a small car agree to take turns.

0239902301264972BBBCCA7AAA7DCE92.description: Child uses reasoning and planning ahead to solve problems.

0C7C67777DF0492AAE23F54AB4D1D25B.description: Tries to solve the same problem in several different ways at different times.

47ED2D28C8CB4F5CA2AFBBA2F983AB8B.description: Uses a variety of strategies to solve problems, such as trial and error, simple tools, or asking someone to help.

F38B8B47D27F4AD6A60C6558635B9FC1.description: Engages in activities for longer periods of time and tries several times to solve more challenging problems, often using a combination of actions or behaviors.

67217F88B1014DA88C029B517F43D9CC.description: Child learns to use a variety of strategies in solving problems.

6F0721D1F8064AB9A1B63C9772642E91.description: Repeats simple rules about expected behavior, such as “We wash our hands before we eat.

30C548CA5A684705B041A6AF8DB764CB.description: Prepares for next routine or activity based on past experiences, such as gets hat or coat when it is time to go outside.

7BA6B645F4A34E528505770B2A1FBD5C.description: Recalls a similar family event when hearing a story read.

952B76D978894611A63CE14556640922.description: Tells others about memories and past experiences. Remembers how to do a series of actions that were observed at an earlier time.

2E6B8118293045EC815C306FEE3BCBC4.description: Child uses memories as a foundation for more complex actions and thoughts.

E340A87967714B84BCB77FAF35F93B60.description: Looks in several different places for a toy that was played with a few days before.

DFF0CACA16A9441AB16E914A2228F884.description: Notices who is missing from a familiar group, such as family at dinner or children in a playgroup.

2345119D938F43D19ABFEFEEF5C37BF1.description: Uses a variety of search strategies to find hidden or missing people or objects, including looking in multiple locations for things that have been missing for some time.

BADA623320F342CEA625F24EA9AFCA74.description: Child recognizes the stability of people and objects in the environment.

E25F2C0753E4454785D03AF4E2322A31.description: Tells others about what will happen next or about changes in usual routines or schedules.

750A2A8A017A41B29F613F8B79D93446.description: Comments about similarities or differences between new people, objects, or events, and ones that are more familiar.

59CE53D0D9D84C0B863522D045066168.description: Anticipates and communicates about multiple steps of familiar routines, activities, or events. Expresses surprise or asks about unexpected outcomes or unusual people, actions, or events.

658F6300522F4DC9AE8E4D8E54B608A2.description: Child recognizes differences between familiar and unfamiliar people, objects, actions, or events.

5B6818A7F6FD4D2487697532E14E22C0.description: Anticipates some cause and effects of own actions, such as what happens while running with a cup of water.

7DB1945080714192A6142179DC89A9CC.description: Makes simple predictions about what will happen next, such as in a story or in everyday routines.

720F0A887441419EAE15BFC22BA55CAD.description: Identifies the cause of an observed outcome, such as the tower fell over because it was built too high. Predicts outcomes of actions or events, such as turning the faucet will make water come out.

5B9D2BBCCC4A4FDF9B9335D1DB289370.description: Child uses understanding of causal relationships to act on social and physical environments.

63FAA55B2EAA40AAAA3B615D8C282E7D.description: Experiments with everyday objects or materials to answer “What?”, “Why?” or “How?” questions.

AA760BE4731842D399BCE04ECF4E9C73.description: Learns about characteristics of people and properties and uses of objects through the senses and active exploration.

9AE31F1CB2D6428AA43B9C0F5CD91389.description: Observes and experiments with how things work, seeks information from others, or experiments with different behaviors to see how people and objects react.

B0C6ADD33DF34CE5A759748DF145CA16.description: Child actively explores people and objects to understand self, others, and objects.

50A0D6AD86AF4FC2B035742825CD2F2C.description: Makes letter-like marks or scribbles on paper.

060592667331413C828E5320353630AD.description: Draws straight lines or curved lines.

F885935475C8470486743EF620389328.description: Draws pictures using scribbles and talks with others about what they have made.

8DEC181986254449B66065CB0A597010.description: Makes scribbles on paper to represent an object or action even though an adult might not recognize what it is.

CE0FD18D88EE43E396A08E9F8F42A418.description: Child makes marks and uses them to represent objects or actions.

AA2AD420FC544874B90A47CCBA272B13.description: Identifies the feelings of characters in a book or story.

023416BAF4CB435384ADF4AE29D55C3E.description: Asks or answers questions about what is happening in a book or story.

287DA1C4202D48DC8A82EBB4ED290C21.description: Uses pictures as a guide to talk about a story that has been read.

B2BEC2A5EA654DCF86004C6D0ADC7285.description: Talks about books, acts out events from stories, and uses some vocabulary encountered during book reading.

10A0D21EB5984EAB9EC1AFFBA2507585.description: Child comprehends meaning from pictures and stories.

390291C1D0CD49F699CE8D432B73516D.description: Attributes meaning to some symbols, such as a familiar logo or design.

DD57F422F2994122A3D097C9ABBB1DBA.description: Recognizes familiar signs on a building or street.

DFBF44E98B1E4DC4ABCD0D0935E5B2CD.description: Points to and names some letters or characters in their names.

593FD92FFB1A408FA46AF24557BBCEA1.description: Recognizes and uses some letters or numbers, such as letters in one’s name, and shows increasing interest in written forms of language, such as print in books or signs on buildings. Children who are DLLs recognize and use written forms of each of their languages.

C68CCE4B7F42408DB0D80525D7A7966C.description: Child recognizes pictures and some symbols, signs, or words.

AD55D551162F4D60A4BD9DB0975AB1F0.description: Holds book, turns pages, and pretends to read.

931A4329DFC14D7CA94C7934B428A345.description: Asks to have several favorite books read over and over.

BA8339B6700544D4824C42D9E267773F.description: Pretends to read books by turning pages and talking about or using signs to describe what is happening in the book.

C52A88255D5D44EC899286DFB46E7408.description: Child handles books and relates them to their stories or information.

93D769F4667A4EA1B409696F108A72E4.description: Repeats simple familiar rhymes or sings favorite songs.

137DCCBCB5984E8F8215ECC4EC50A567.description: Says or repeats culturally and linguistically familiar rhymes, phrases, or refrains from songs or stories.

E2ED5B6ED022483EA34B7FE99CF37765.description: Child attends to, repeats, and uses some rhymes, phrases, or refrains from stories or songs.

6A6259EDC99C4FF488619D2FDB9D6F4F.description: Asks questions about the meaning of new words.

C6F36CAD0E784F0882A22CFE0C9A22C5.description: Demonstrates a vocabulary of at least 300 words in home language.

7D075F0556E642068C3C1F621FC38C17.description: Shows rapid growth in number of words or signs used in conversation with others.

42F4110F254E45E691F6B89001B4DDF3.description: Uses an increasing number of words in communication and conversation with others and adds new vocabulary words regularly. Children who are DLLs may have a combined vocabulary in both languages that is similar in number to other children’s vocabulary in one language.

C9C2B396CADA4A55B6F2D3358D1BE98C.description: Child uses an increasing number of words in communication and conversation with others.

597AF52E88ED45F786A535DB4B95EFA1.description: Understands most positional words, such as on, under, up, or down.

7DCE46DD35D04CB784DDAF160643B0EA.description: Attends to new words used in conversation with others.

F92BB014467645499B9D60CCA94D82D8.description: Shows understanding of the meaning of common words used in daily activities.

FECA389FCB8048FC82B2A89ABEDB7D11.description: Comprehends an increasing number of words or signs used in simple sentences during conversation and interaction with familiar adults and children.

B2F5A129CDDE455BA1D155180FDF3862.description: Child understands an increasing number of words used in communication with others.

708D724FE489437E85936A5C64508623.description: Repeats or re-phrases questions until a response is received.

27BCA52C8AEB449EB4CEE750C4FBFFEF.description: Asks questions in a variety of ways.

41F6D0F73A4A4396B61FA99CCEE05EF8.description: Seeks information and meaning of words by asking questions in words or signs, such as “What’s that?” or “Who’s that?” or “Why?”

291143B867E34A849C1F038185C93A09.description: Child initiates non-verbal communication and language to learn and gain information.

B6D1EC7EEFBD47A0B435172B491432C1.description: Refers to past or future events in conversation with others.

FF4FBEA57DFA4731AFD6C2C1EC59F10D.description: Asks and answers simple questions in conversations with others.

BE3621C2B996474984C81928AAAEF3FC.description: Uses sentences of three or more words in conversation with others.

CB54256A0BBB4455BA7E2960759138EC.description: Participates in conversations with others using spoken or sign language that includes simple sentences, questions, and responses. Sometimes describes experiences that have happened in the past or are about to happen. Children who are DLLs develop the ability to participate in conversations with increasing complexity in each of their languages.

82620B6283974953A91A5FBE390F034C.description: Child uses increasingly complex language in conversation with others.

5DDAB9EB1629423392FEB1C5A156F884.description: Engages in simple conversations by expressing own feelings, thoughts, and ideas to others.

1CF7E0ACDE02478FB121387BA26BF00B.description: Participates in simple conversations with others that are maintained by back-andforth exchanges of ideas or information.

AA475CEF6BF1499AA3FD0AA18616A809.description: Initiates and responds in conversations with others.

718ADEACD37C40EBBE7FDED4E11F6DFF.description: Uses words, signs, phrases, or simple sentences to initiate, continue, or extend conversations with others about feelings, experiences, or thoughts.

A7FE4C2ECE7A4B61B3D584F836768A0F.description: Child uses non-verbal communication and language to engage others in interaction.

6A08052C84C24FF9981D6868D621028F.description: Uses simple sentences, such as 3–4 word sentences, to communicate needs and wants.

F4010858F8C24FAB953C5CD3E901AA71.description: Uses combinations of words and simple sentences or signs in a variety of situations.

1A8378DE67BE4F6CB7584F03EB2F7FAB.description: Combines words or signs from one or more languages into phrases and sentences to communicate needs, wants, or ideas, such as “More milk,” “I want juice,” “Mas leche,” or “Quiero juice.” Children who are dual language learners may combine their two languages or switch between them.

1F760D2B69C149658B2C3B28FB93728A.description: Child communicates needs and wants non-verbally and by using language.

86263F2D5B4F4A81A407491244599847.description: Demonstrates interest and understanding when participating in language activities or games.

8D7A7629934A44A6B98568B7D383F5B7.description: Acts on descriptions provided by others about people, objects, or events.

413CE22ACF9E45569FCB4134A98225B0.description: Participates in increasingly complex and lengthy periods of joint attention with adults. Shows interest, understanding, or enjoyment when participating in language activities, such as demonstrating understanding of objects’ functions and uses, or when joining in games, songs, rhymes, or stories.

1E0536B5653A4C9C8130F12063D8FDA1.description: Child learns from communication and language experiences with others.

C6F8E11C542B4084A36444AEC6D7CA1F.description: Shows comprehension of simple sentences, such as by listening to and following one- or two-step directions.

140FE77A14824102BF25F83BA381FA3F.description: Shows understanding of some words and phrases used in conversation, such as by responding to simple questions.

4DF52DB0ECAC4B23A5B0DD2886F65C0D.description: Shows recognition of words, phrases, and simple sentences. Participates in conversations in ways that show understanding by following comments or suggestions with actions or behavior.

0A7E0F0501D641A6A4AA144B21391018.description: Child attends to, understands, and responds to communication and language from others.

BABCBEA8061D4F98805562F5C736140A.description: Talks about family members, familiar people, or friends who may not be present.

501ADCA5BE6046FF888E07223B0172EA.description: Points to or names self and other familiar people, such as in photos or pictures.

90314E4EA48143E4AF8C5D3E28F99C8F.description: Identifies self as a member of a family.

F80E11D132154B748288121991BAA7B5.description: Refers  to personal or family experiences and events that have happened in the recent past, such as when gradparent came to visit or when there was a family celebration.

6138B1476006413D99566E4B7560DD5C.description: Child develops a sense of belonging through relationships with others.

F860D7920F3041E2A9E70A517E8521E2.description: Shows others what they can do.

F8C9C90E09FD486387422C876738A569.description: Constributes own ideas, skills, and abilities to activities and experiences with adults and other children. May call attention to new skills and abilities or seek to do things by self, such as putting on own jacket or pouring juice out of a smaller pitcher.

0340830464BD4B0483B0A2202C54FCAC.description: Child shows confidence in own abilities through relationships with others.

C705771801D04FD7990BD5DBEE21EFAC.description: Recognizes some similarities and differences between self and others.

47D1BC2C97C6482682F6AEA516F34B72.description: Identifies some physical characteristics of self such as hair color, age, gender, or size.

FD2C6E6664F74C2682E47F686422F85E.description: Identifies obvious physical similarities and diffrences between self and others. Compares characteristics of self and others.

1D49769D3FA34DC0A530A5B7DB8E473B.description: Child understands some chracteristics of self and others.

A6CC4D5D7AA14301A83051923C645DB7.description: Shows awareness of others as having thoughts and feelings separate from own.

646DA2CF8B574A2A8C112D405D4310E5.description: Shows areness of self including own body, abilities, thoughts, and feelings.

611F0AA5FB14497D87E0F1604D956D1F.description: Shows awareness of own thoughts, feelins, and preferences as well as those of othhers. Uses different words or signs to refer to self and others.

A24DEF3C1ED740E9B1681E2F089B6944.description: Child shows awareness about self and how to connect with others.

A47E63A4EF3F4842AF89F62A5E4871E3.description: SUB-DOMAIN: SENSE OF IDENTITY AND BELONGING
